{"ts":"2026-06-27T21:24:06.647Z","type":"agent_event","event":{"type":"content_end","contentType":"reasoning","reasoning":"**Checking API Integrations**\n\nI've confirmed the insertion's success. Now, I'm focusing on those powerful helpers in `lib/dynamodb-client.ts`. My immediate question is whether we need to update the Next.js API route files in `app/api/v1/` to leverage them. I need to make sure those API routes are correctly calling the helpers to access the database.\n\n\n**Analyzing Mock Data Access**\n\nI've just realized a critical point about the mock data. Examining `app/api/v1/projects/route.ts`, I see it directly modifies `API_MOCK_PROJECTS`. This object is also accessed through our new DynamoDB helpers in `lib/dynamodb-client.ts` because `API_MOCK_PROJECTS` is a reference to `(global as any)._apiMockProjects`. Therefore, switching to the helpers for mock mode keeps the mocks perfectly in sync. In mock mode, the helpers will modify the EXACT SAME memory objects. This has huge implications for testing and existing code!\n\n\n**Listing API Routes**\n\nI'm thinking about making all API routes use the helpers, so I've just listed all the Next.js API route files. It turns out there are a lot, so I need to update 13 files! This will be a significant change but will improve consistency and DynamoDB interaction.\n\n\n**Considering Update Scope**\n\nI'm now contemplating the scale of these updates. Initially, updating all routes seemed straightforward. However, seeing the list of 13 files is giving me pause. Maybe there's a more efficient approach? The task requirements seem clear, but I should double-check them for nuances. It appears \"backend check\" means the Python tests, which already passed. So, now I need to check the Next.js routes.\n\n\n"}}
